On 10 Nov 2012, at 08:54, Mike Nickerson wrote:

> Hi Rush,
> 
> Peltier coolers do have some significant advantages (small size, no moving
> parts, easy to hook up), but they are also rather inefficient.  
> 
> The following write-up does a pretty good job of laying out the pros and
> cons for Peltier devices:
> http://www.tellurex.com/technology/peltier-faq.php
> 
> As an example, the A22 air-to-air cooler at the Tellurex site has a capacity
> rating of 22W (77 BTU/hr) cooling, but requires 72W input to get that
> cooling out.  That will require a pretty good heatsink to get rid of the
> heat in the summer.
> 
> I haven't used any of these devices, but I have friends that have; mostly
> for cooling telescope CCD sensors.  In that application, the lack of moving
> parts and vibrations makes them the only game in town.
> 
> Mike
> 
>> 
>> I can't agree with you more. Here in AZ the summer heat is a real battery
>> killer as now experienced by some Leaf owners. I have a 2000 Insight
> Hybrid
>> and the NIMH battery pack throws a 'bad' battery pack code every day when
>> it is hot. I recharge it, rebalancing the individual cells by slow
> charging at
>> 350mA (the BMS that Honda has cannot do this). Now that is it cooler, 80's
>> during the day, it takes 4 or 5 days before the pack throws the same 'bad'
>> battery pack code.
>> 
>> I've just gotten a new battery pack, made up of new, unused cells and am
>> going to install it today. I keep on thinking about an active cooling
> system.
>> The present system is just a fan that comes on (at 100 deg) to suck air
> from
>> the passenger compartment into and thru the battery pack. So the
> 'cooling',
>> or 'heating' is the same temperature as the passenger compartment. I've
>> made some modifications, but not enough.
>> 
>> I envision something that is based on a Peltier system - does anyone know
> of
>> a module that can be inserted in an air stream that will cool the air
> enough
>> (delta T?) to cool/keep cool the pack?
>> 
>> Thanks
>> Rush
>> www.TucsonEV.com




